segments.text: Okay.
I was on the farm until they disposed of the farm and then I got a job in 1924 for the Veterans Administration at Houston as an agriculture rehabilitation assistant.
That job played out and
Okay, what were your duties as this rehabilitation assistant?
I was consulting, advising veterans of World War I that had what they called projects on different farms.
They were scattered around over Texas.
So you would give them advice on how to succeed in their
Farming.
Yeah, I had to do the farming and take care of some of their personal problems that they were having.
But then that played out in 25.
Yeah, that played out in 25.
Then for that, for another time, I had hard sledding.
I tried to sell insurance.
I like insurance.
I imagine that wasn't a great deal of fun, was it?
No, that wasn't fun either.
Then in
29 I went with the Department of Agriculture.
And I've been there, I was there until I retired.
And did you come directly to El Paso?
Yes.
And was in the Department of Agriculture?
Came in the Department of Agriculture as a plant quarantine inspector.
came as what they call an agent, but I took the examination in November 19, uh, 20, 29.
The time played out here in El Paso County and I was sent to, to, uh, in Arizona, Sentinel, Arizona.
Well, in something out of Arizona, they got my grades and I had passed one out of, one of the seven of 49 that passed, I was one, and they sent me back here to El Paso.
And I was then transferred in March 30 to Phavens and spent five years down in Phavens.
and then transferred back up to El Paso in 35 and been here ever since.
You said you were a plant inspector?
Yeah, plant quarantine inspector.
So in that position, what did you do?
It was a station on the border on the, and inspected fruits and vegetables that came from Mexico.
Into the United States.
Yeah.
So would you say if a man wanted to bring a truckload of oranges from Mexico into El Paso, you would inspect them?
Well, some of that fruit's been prohibited.
We were looking for prohibited fruit.
Not very many of those fruits could pass.
Did you have any particular exciting incidents while you were in?
Working on the border?
No, I went through it pretty quietly.
Was it, what would you call it, smuggling?
People wanting to bring in illegal fruit or something?
Oh yeah, there's... Was there a good bit of that?
There's not too much of it.
During the time that you were on duty there from...

the late what late 20s 29 up to your retirement what did you say would you say it was an increase or a decrease or did you remain about the same well i don't know the traffic increased and of course that would increase it would increase it but it would be i guess it would increase
But say, you wouldn't be able to tell probably whether it was increased in the same proportion of the amount of traffic or not, huh?
No.
And at what point did you retire from the quarantine?
Was it the quarantine service?
Yeah.
Department of Agriculture?
Quarantine service.
April the 30th.
So how have you been occupying your time since then?
I've been enjoying most of the time, but I had a heart attack in in 59, a year after I retired, and for four years there I was held down pretty good, but after that I went on, went on pretty good.
Do you participate in any kind of social or cultural or political activities?
No, I'm strictly a home man.
Just strictly a home man, huh?
Okay.
